quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Composition[/h1]

In the real world, complex objects are typically built using smaller, simpler objects. For example, a car is assembled using a metal frame, an engine, tires, and a large number of other parts. This process is called [b]composition[/b].

In C++, object composition involves using classes as member variables in other classes.
This sample program demonstrates composition in action. It contains [b]Person [/b]and [b]Birthday [/b]classes, and each [b]Person [/b]will have a [b]Birthday [/b]object as its member.
[b]Birthday:[/b] [code format="cpp"]class Birthday {
 public:
  Birthday(int m, int d, int y)
  : month(m), day(d), year(y)
  { 
  }
 private:
   int month;
   int day;
   int year;
};[/code]
Our [b]Birthday [/b]class has three member variables. It also has a constructor that initializes the members using a member initialization list.
[note]The class was declared in a single file for the sake of simplicity. Alternatively, you could use header and source files.[/note]

